    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA18-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piriviṭai āṟṟāḷākiya talaiviyait (ET: talaimakaḷait) tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante comforted HER who was unable to bear it in the time of separation.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA18">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            paruvara ṉeñcamoṭu palpaṭa rakala</l>
<l>            varuvarkol vāḻi tōḻi mūvaṉ </l>
<l>            muḻuvali muḷḷeyi ṟaḻuttiya kataviṟ</l>
<l>            kāṉalan toṇṭip porunaṉ veṉvēṟ</l>
<l>            ṟeṟalarun tāṉaip poṟaiyaṉ pācaṟai </l>
<l>            neñca naṭukkuṟūun tuñcā maṟavar</l>
<l>            tiraitapu kaṭali ṉiṉitukaṇ paṭuppak</l>
<l>            kaṭāaṅ kaḻīiya kataṉaṭaṅ kiyāṉait</l>
<l>            taṭavunilai yorukōṭ ṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>            voṉṟilaṅ karuviya kuṉṟiṟan tōrē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>            So that many worries may depart from [my] afflicted heart,</l>
<l>            will he come, oh friend?</l>
<l>            – the one who traversed the hills with a single shining waterfall,</l>
<l rend="indent2">like the broad-based one tusk of the elephant</l>
<l rend="indent3">whose fury is subdued when [its] must washes off,</l>
<l rend="indent">so that the sleepless warriors<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṟavar</term> usually refers to the plunderers of the desert region, but here it seems to mean simply warriors.</note>, whose hearts [he] made tremble,</l>
<l rend="indent">pleasantly close [their] eyes, like when the waves subside in the sea,</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the encampment of the Poṟaiyaṉ with an army of rare wrath</l>
<l rend="indent3">[and] victorious spears, the leader of Toṇṭi on the seashore,</l>
<l rend="indent3">in anger against Mūvaṉ pressing together [his] thorn teeth</l>
<l rend="indent4">with full strength.<note place="foot">Line 3 is peculiar, to put it mildly. T.V.G. explains that <term xml:lang="ta">Poṟaiyaṉ</term> had the teeth (presumably with the jaw) of his enemy <term xml:lang="ta">Mūvaṉ</term> impressed on his door - in the way other victors put the head of an enemy on a stake at their gate. But there are no parallels to attest such a custom.</note></l>
            
            </lg>
         </div>
